goals.rationale: This visualization will show the median, quartiles, and outliers of the stock prices, giving an idea of the spread and skewness of the data.

goals.visualization: line chart of price over date, with separate lines for each company
goals.rationale: This visualization will show how the stock prices of each company have changed over time, allowing for comparisons and identification of trends.

goals.question: Which company had the highest average stock price over the entire period?
goals.visualization: bar chart of mean price for each company
goals.rationale: This visualization will show the mean stock price for each company, allowing for easy comparison and identification of the company with the highest average price.

goals.question: What is the correlation between stock prices of different companies?

goals.rationale: This visualization will show the relationship between the stock prices of two companies, allowing for identification of any patterns or trends in the data.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%b %d %Y', errors='coerce')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.boxplot(data['price'], vert=False, showfliers=True, patch_artist=True, boxprops=dict(facecolor='lightblue', color='black'), medianprops=dict(color='black'), whiskerprops=dict(color='black'), capprops=dict(color='black'))
    ax.set_xlabel('Price')
    ax.set_yticklabels([''])
    plt.title('What is the distribution of stock prices across all companies?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%b %d %Y', errors='coerce')
    companies = data['symbol'].unique()
    for company in companies:
        company_data = data[data['symbol'] == company]
        plt.plot(company_data['date'], company_data['price'], label=company)
    plt.title('What is the trend of stock prices for each company over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%b %d %Y', errors='coerce')
    data = data.groupby(['symbol']).mean().reset_index()
    data = data.sort_values(by=['price'], ascending=False)
    plt.bar(data['symbol'], data['price'])
    plt.axhline(y=data['price'].max(), color='r', linestyle='-')
    plt.legend(['Max Price'])
    plt.title('Which company had the highest average stock price over the entire period?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%b %d %Y', errors='coerce')
    ibm = data[data['symbol'] == 'IBM']
    goog = data[data['symbol'] == 'GOOG']
    plt.scatter(ibm['price'], goog['price'])
    plt.xlabel('IBM')
    plt.ylabel('GOOG')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between stock prices of different companies?')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%b %d %Y', errors='coerce')
    date_count = data.groupby('date')['price'].count()
    plt.hist(date_count, bins=20, color='green')
    plt.axvline(date_count.median(), color='red', label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(date_count.median()))
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of the number of stock prices recorded for each date?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
